WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.660 --> 00:00:06.720
Hi, I'm Sarah Meister.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.800
I'm a curator here in the Department of Photography
at MoMA and we're thrilled to be bringing

00:00:11.809 --> 00:00:16.150
you a live Q&amp;A on MoMA's YouTube channel.

00:00:16.150 --> 00:00:19.820
We are gonna begin here on the collection
storage while people get settled.

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:23.640
This is where we store a huge percentage of
our collection.

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:29.210
And we thought it'd be fun to pull some photographs
to show you a few before we get going with

00:00:29.210 --> 00:00:31.159
the real Q&amp;A.

00:00:31.159 --> 00:00:35.160
And while we do that, I'll not only try to
answer a few of the questions not formally,

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:39.840
but a little informally, starting with, say,
show me a surprise,

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.720
something that's a little lesser known treasure
in the collection.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:49.180
So we also thought it would be a nice thing
to show you how we store the photographs,

00:00:49.180 --> 00:00:52.400
why we store the photographs, and to share
a bit of our best practices.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:55.970
So most of the collections are in cabinets
like this.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:57.360
It keeps the water off.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:00.470
If the sprinklers go, that would be bad.

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:03.900
It keeps them nice and cold.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:08.140
And we keep them in boxes, usually whenever
we can, unless they're too big.

00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:15.280
So here's a box that has some works that we
acquired a little more than a year ago.

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:19.680
We try not to carry the boxes long distances,
so we don't risk dropping them, because that

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:22.090
would be terrible.

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:25.340
And then when we open them, these are all
archival materials.

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:28.439
We try to keep everything sort of neat and
calm.

00:01:28.439 --> 00:01:32.639
We try when we're handling photographs to
like focus on the photograph and not focus

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:34.869
on, say, talking to you all.

00:01:34.869 --> 00:01:37.750
So we don't damage anything.

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:43.090
So this is a box of works by a Brazilian photographer
named Gertrudes Altschul.

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:47.310
She's one of my current favorites, although
I can't say all time, because that's just

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:48.999
not fair.

00:01:48.999 --> 00:01:52.340
And the one I thought I would show you is
here on the bottom.

00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:57.450
It's a photograph of a papaya leaf.

00:01:57.450 --> 00:01:59.770
It's pretty awesome.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.970
What I love about it is that it looks a little
bit like a photogram, almost like you could

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:04.970
see through it.

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:07.799
Like she was squishing it flat onto the paper.

00:02:07.799 --> 00:02:12.920
Except that when you see the stem, you realize
that this is actually like a three-dimensional

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:14.560
object in front of the camera.

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.100
So I like this one a lot.

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:18.860
This is a little bit of a surprise.

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:23.360
It was on view last year if you came to New
York in a show that my colleague Starr and

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:24.920
I organized called

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:28.450
"Making Space: Women Artists and Post War
Abstraction."

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:33.560
But other than that, I'm sure no one had...well,
unless you lived in Sao Paolo, you had not

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:35.280
seen it before.

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:38.060
So this is how we keep them.

00:02:38.060 --> 00:02:42.160
This is fortunately not too heavy, some of
them get really heavy, and then we have to

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:47.070
have a colleague come help us take them down
off the shelf.

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:48.820
Okay.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:52.960
So this is not the official Q&amp;A, but we thought
we'd answer a few questions while we're in

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.870
here anyway.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:03:02.180
The first question, unofficially, is from
Victoria on Instagram and Danny on YouTube,

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:03.940
who both asked, basically,

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:06.530
"What is the temperature in there and why?

00:03:06.530 --> 00:03:10.180
Or why is the collection storage space so
cold?"

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:16.510
So it's about 50 degrees in here, 40% relative
humidity.

00:03:16.510 --> 00:03:19.640
And yesterday when I was getting ready for
this, I asked our conservator.

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:23.360
I was like, "How do I describe why it's so
cold?"

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:26.240
And her answer was...I was thinking she was
gonna give me some complicated chemical or

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:27.220
something.

00:03:27.220 --> 00:03:31.440
She's like, "Everything goes more slowly when
it's cold."

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:36.210
And so if you think of the photographs having
active particles in them, the more you slow

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:38.970
it down, the longer they live.

00:03:38.970 --> 00:03:44.650
So this is true for color photographs, especially,
but also for gelatin silver prints, like most

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:46.350
of what we'll be looking at today.

00:03:46.350 --> 00:03:50.120
So it's cold to keep everything lasting as
long as possible.

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.010
And that's also why we use archival materials.

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:55.430
I just washed my hands.

00:03:55.430 --> 00:03:59.069
So if you see me handling a lot of things,
I wouldn't do that unless I had just washed

00:03:59.069 --> 00:04:00.570
my hands.

00:04:00.570 --> 00:04:03.490
So that's question number one.

00:04:03.490 --> 00:04:08.290
We have another question that says...and this
is from Chris on Instagram.

00:04:08.290 --> 00:04:12.400
And he writes, "What is your collection policy?

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.760
And Alfred Stieglitz, please."

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:16.910
So excellent choice, Alfred.

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:18.690
No, Alfred Stieglitz.

00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:20.070
Excellent choice, Chris.

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:23.410
I pulled a few extra, a little bit like a
cooking show because sometimes if you have

00:04:23.410 --> 00:04:26.290
to take them down, we have to go too far and
it takes too long.

00:04:26.290 --> 00:04:31.530
So I pulled three other photographs, including
the Stieglitz just to show while we're here

00:04:31.530 --> 00:04:35.280
in collection storage getting warmed up.

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:41.290
The first one of these, I mean, I'll say,
everything I'm showing, I love all these photographs,

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:43.100
but this one is pretty great.

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:48.180
Now you'll see there's a little bit of a reflective
surface on this, and I'll lift it off to make

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:49.610
it easier to see.

00:04:49.610 --> 00:04:51.180
This is called Mylar.

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:55.550
It protects the surface of the picture in
storage and we actually attach it with tape

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:59.260
at the top, but it's a special low tack tape.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:03.810
So this is a photograph by Berenice Abbott
and it's called "New York at Night."

00:05:03.810 --> 00:05:09.130
She made it in 1932 right after the Empire
State Building opened.

00:05:09.130 --> 00:05:14.480
And she made it on one of the shortest days
of the year, so in sort of mid to late December.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:17.950
And she did that because she wanted the city
to be dark,

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:22.160
but she wanted everyone to still be in their
offices so that all the thousands and thousands

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:23.960
of office lights are on.

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:27.330
So it's almost like you couldn't make this
picture in the summer because it would be

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:28.380
light too late.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:31.870
And by the time was dark, everybody would
be gone home for the day.

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:33.940
I hope.

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:38.250
So this is a terrific one and I can't remember
who but somebody definitely wanted to see

00:05:38.250 --> 00:05:39.380
Berenice Abbott.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:41.690
So that's one.

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:46.300
And then, you know, again, like I was saying,
you just wanna handle them carefully,

00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:52.240
slowly because, of course, the worst thing
you could ever do to a photograph is damage it.

00:05:52.380 --> 00:05:54.480
That would just be the worst.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:06:00.850
The next photograph I wanted to show you,
again, thanks to Chris asking for Alfred Stieglitz,

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:05.120
"this terrific image of Stieglitz's made?"

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:14.480
I'm just gonna do this because Stieglitz really...although
Berenice Abbott was a little more forgiving

00:06:14.490 --> 00:06:17.520
about the presentation, Stieglitz was very
precise.

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:25.800
So here's a photograph he made of his wife
Georgia O'Keeffe and her car.

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:27.300
And what I love about this one.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:29.580
This is at his house in Lake George.

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:35.600
And to me, he's very well known for the group
of portraits that he made of Georgia O'Keeffe.

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:42.460
But to me, this is sort of a symbol of her
independence, how by 1935 she was definitely

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:46.350
a mature artist in her own right, had much
more of a sense of autonomy.

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:50.690
And I think there's something almost sort
of wistful about this thinking of her hopping

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:53.740
in the car, and maybe going back to New York
City.

00:06:53.740 --> 00:07:01.200
And so even though the photograph is so beautiful,
and you'd see the sky reflected on the paint finish

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:05.480
it still makes me think there must have been
something about this car that made him feel

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:09.740
a little wistful or makes me feel wistful,
please.

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:17.580
So, again, the other thing I try not to do
is to actually, and this is super easy to

00:07:17.590 --> 00:07:18.590
do at home,

00:07:18.590 --> 00:07:22.650
don't talk over your photos, because everybody
spits when they talk.

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:27.180
And especially if you're standing right over
it, you should be careful.

00:07:27.180 --> 00:07:31.550
Because spit is not a good friend to photographs
as you might imagine.

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:32.850
All right.

00:07:32.850 --> 00:07:40.070
And then the last one I pulled for us to look
at today is this huge, beautiful print.

00:07:40.070 --> 00:07:43.650
Well, kind of gritty, maybe beautiful is the
wrong word.

00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:47.170
I'm gonna leave the Mylar on it because it's
too complicated to take this one off.

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:53.120
This is by a photographer named Gordon Parks,
and it's from a photo story that he did for

00:07:53.120 --> 00:08:00.580
"Life Magazine" called "The Atmosphere of
Crime" in 1957.

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:04.090
It's actually, I learned more recently, a
color photograph.

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:08.120
But it was super difficult to print in color
back in the 1950s.

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:09.630
It was very expensive.

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:14.820
So even though in the magazine, a lot of his
photographs are reproduced in color, the print

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:19.680
we own that we acquired from Gordon Parks
is actually in black and white.

00:08:19.680 --> 00:08:24.979
And so it's something I think is really interesting
to think about, like, what makes photographers

00:08:24.979 --> 00:08:26.260
make the choices they do?

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:28.850
And sometimes it can be an incredibly practical
thing.

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:33.490
Like, it's way too expensive to make a color
photograph in the '50s.

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:38.570
So instead, you kind of heighten the graphic
quality and you make it in black and white.

00:08:38.570 --> 00:08:46.950
So I also thought it would be fun while we're
here to look for one last picture, to look

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:48.580
at a recent acquisition.

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:52.100
And these are...if we'd been here a week ago,

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:56.149
I wouldn't be able to show this to you because
it would have been a secret because our committee

00:08:56.149 --> 00:08:58.899
on photography wouldn't have approved it yet,

00:08:58.899 --> 00:09:02.470
but now it's all approved so I can show you.

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:09.020
So we saw a few things framed and these are
the framed ones, but sometimes something so

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:14.060
big, it's here only temporarily like for an
acquisitions meeting.

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:17.240
Super careful.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:25.080
Now, for those of you at home, this is not
part of the photograph, this is just a string

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:27.550
to make sure it doesn't fall off.

00:09:27.550 --> 00:09:29.540
That would be terrible.

00:09:29.540 --> 00:09:35.390
But this is an incredible photograph by Deana
Lawson that was in her exhibition, not that

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:37.520
long ago at Sikkema Jenkins.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:46.980
It's really an incredibly powerful and, you
know, even bordering on scary photograph.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:55.060
And I love also that a new aspect of her work
is she has included the sort of image that's

00:09:55.060 --> 00:10:00.170
affixed to the outside of the Plexiglas, so
this is a new aspect of her work.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:07.180
She was actually honored last night as one
of the honorees at the Gordon Parks Foundation

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:07.960
Gala.

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:10.760
So that was nice to see her and celebrate
her there.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:13.670
And I thought to myself, "And we just acquired
it."

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:16.830
So let's get out of here.

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:17.540
It's cold.

00:10:17.560 --> 00:10:18.620
I'm sure there are enough people.

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:21.520
We'll go do a real Q&amp;A in the study center.

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:22.860
Thanks for joining me.

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:53.360
All right.

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:57.880
Here we are in Collection...no, now we're
out of Collection Storage.

00:10:57.890 --> 00:11:03.830
My hands are cold, my face is cold, but we
are going to have fun out here.

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:07.060
I have a whole pile of questions to answer.

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:12.459
We got so many great ones from the trailer,
both on Instagram and on YouTube.

00:11:12.459 --> 00:11:13.630
We picked some of my favorites.

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:17.590
And I'll apologize in advance that we won't
get to do everyone's, but we'll really do

00:11:17.590 --> 00:11:19.270
our best.

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:23.460
If you have any other questions, we're also
gonna try to work in some questions that are

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:24.930
submitted live.

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:29.839
So there's a little live chat section.

00:11:29.839 --> 00:11:33.459
And I have some colleagues here who are gonna
write down your questions and give them to

00:11:33.459 --> 00:11:37.690
me, and then we'll try to answer those as
well.

00:11:37.690 --> 00:11:39.640
All right, let's get to the questions.

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:44.339
Okay.

00:11:44.339 --> 00:11:53.180
The first one is from Anastasia from YouTube
and she writes, "What aspect of the work should

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:56.980
we focus on first, when we visit a photography
exhibition?"

00:11:56.980 --> 00:12:00.300
And I think that's such an excellent question.

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:01.640
It's like, what do you think about?

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:04.459
You walk in, let's say, you don't know the
work, what are you gonna look at?

00:12:04.459 --> 00:12:07.709
How are you going to think about it?

00:12:07.709 --> 00:12:12.279
I like to see an exhibition...at first, I
like to just look at the work.

00:12:12.279 --> 00:12:16.870
So you try to do sort of a sweep through and
you think to yourself, "Let's look at what

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:18.150
this artist is doing.

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:21.790
What are they doing in terms of scale, what
are they doing in terms of subject matter?

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:26.360
Do there seem to be important things about
the materiality of what they're doing?"

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:29.290
And you kind of just get a general feel.

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:34.710
If I'm at a gallery or at a museum, then I
usually go up and I try to read the wall text.

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:40.230
I would recommend not doing that first because
it kind of opens up a little bit more what

00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:45.200
your experience can be, if you've had a little
time with the art first.

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:51.779
And then after that, chances are, I'll go
back again and maybe the second time around,

00:12:51.779 --> 00:12:55.620
you pick fewer pictures, but you just dive
in a little deeper.

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:59.840
When I go with my children, I call it a surgical
strike.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:05.560
So with them, I might skip the first and the
second parts and just say, "Okay, we're gonna

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:07.360
look closely at three pictures.

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:08.360
And that's it."

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:12.260
And, you know, that can be a really rewarding
thing, too, is just sort of slowing down enough

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:15.050
to look at just a couple of things.

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:17.560
But that's an excellent question.

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:19.210
Thank you.

00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:21.470
Carrying on.

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:30.760
Okay, Mac J. on Instagram wrote, "Are there
specific steps one can take to become a curator

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.850
of photography?"

00:13:33.850 --> 00:13:35.600
Another good question.

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:43.020
I would say, yes, there are typical ones and
then there are less typical ones.

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:49.620
The typical one might be an art history major
in college.

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:54.459
And then you might try to get some practical
work experience.

00:13:54.459 --> 00:14:01.829
So let's say you go work in a gallery, or
an auction house or a museum and you try to

00:14:01.829 --> 00:14:05.580
sort of get some experience working with real
works of art.

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:10.860
And then most photography curators go to graduate
school.

00:14:10.860 --> 00:14:15.740
I happen to be an exception to that, but it's,
particularly this day and age, much, much

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:16.800
more common.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:24.329
So I would say it's a combination of school,
work experience.

00:14:24.329 --> 00:14:28.370
And then the nice thing is, and the way I
feel here at MoMA is like, your learning goes

00:14:28.370 --> 00:14:29.370
on and on.

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:35.890
So although I'm not specifically in school
anymore, I always try to go see as much art

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:36.890
as I can.

00:14:36.890 --> 00:14:38.180
I try to read a lot.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:44.399
I try to have conversations with my colleagues
to try to understand the way they see things.

00:14:44.399 --> 00:14:49.329
And traveling is also a really wonderful way
if you're able to,

00:14:49.329 --> 00:14:52.910
to try to understand how people see things
and do things differently in other parts of

00:14:52.910 --> 00:14:53.910
the world,

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:58.260
which can be hard, but that's optimal if you
can do that.

00:14:59.860 --> 00:15:00.900
We're okay?

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:03.600
All right.

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:10.920
So A. Wiedler wrote on Instagram, "I love
Helen Levitt's work and saw some online at

00:15:10.920 --> 00:15:12.400
MoMA's website."

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:14.200
So guess what, we pulled one.

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:17.480
I love Helen Levitt too.

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:24.620
The first one we pulled is this, one of Helen
Levitt's most famous images.

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:30.420
And this photograph was actually...came into
the collection in...

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:35.540
well, officially accessioned in 1941, but
it was a photograph of Helen Levitt that she

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:38.800
made in 1940 on the streets of New York.

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:41.740
So you have to imagine that's a super short
time.

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:50.209
It's actually not...unlike the Deana Lawson,
where it's a recent work and we're just acquiring

00:15:50.209 --> 00:15:51.209
it,

00:15:51.209 --> 00:15:55.890
that happens less frequently, I would say,
than sometimes a little more time passing.

00:15:55.890 --> 00:16:00.520
But so Helen Levitt made this photograph in
1940, in December of 1940.

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:07.000
We actually exhibited it here at MoMA in the
first exhibit of the formal department of

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:08.000
photography.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.620
Oh, I forgot to mention that.

