00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:42.030
prints, but it's an early print.

00:26:42.030 --> 00:26:46.600
And I thought it might be interesting to look
at this one next to this.

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:52.730
So this is a print of Lange's "Migrant Mother"
that came to us from the "New York Times."

00:26:52.730 --> 00:26:56.710
It has heavy, heavy airbrushing on it.

00:26:56.710 --> 00:27:02.600
So if you look, for instance, you see...and
the way you can tell airbrush is, unlike up

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:07.410
here where you can see that the paint has
been like wash, like painted on.

00:27:07.410 --> 00:27:09.110
You can kind of see the brushstrokes in it.

00:27:09.110 --> 00:27:12.710
When you have airbrushing, it's a super even
look.

00:27:12.710 --> 00:27:16.500
And when you look at it under a microscope,
you can actually see the little, little dots

00:27:16.500 --> 00:27:21.390
from the way that the paint has spat on to
the surface of the picture.

00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:26.070
But it makes for a much more dramatic contrast.

00:27:26.070 --> 00:27:30.429
So when you paint in the dark parts, like
the spaces between their fingers,

00:27:30.429 --> 00:27:34.630
and then you airbrush other parts to make
it look smoother, you can see how,

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:41.800
if you were reproducing this in a newspaper,
let's say, how this photograph would reproduce

00:27:41.800 --> 00:27:43.880
much more cleanly than this.

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:50.160
And, since I sort of promised we would do
this, we...and remember I said I washed my

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:55.090
hands, so if our conservator is watching,
