00:27:55.090 --> 00:28:00.170
The other thing that's great about this photograph,
if we take it out, is that on the back...now,

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:03.580
of course, I'm being so special with this.

00:28:03.580 --> 00:28:08.270
You understand that before this photograph
came to MoMA, thousands of people probably

00:28:08.270 --> 00:28:11.309
held it with the dirtiest hands you can imagine.

00:28:11.309 --> 00:28:12.740
It was circulated.

00:28:12.740 --> 00:28:18.130
Every one of these stamps on the back suggested
or tells a time when it was reproduced in

00:28:18.130 --> 00:28:19.150
the "New York Times."

00:28:19.150 --> 00:28:26.470
So the earliest one that I found is here,
July 26th, 1936, and that is the earliest.

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:29.659
But it actually was reproduced up through
1976.

00:28:29.659 --> 00:28:31.230
That's the most recent stamp.

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:35.270
So this is a photograph that even though now
that it's here at MoMA, we treat it super

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:38.260
precious and we're taking very good care of
it.

00:28:38.260 --> 00:28:45.270
It lived a long very active life in the "New
York Times" photo morgue before it came here,

00:28:45.270 --> 00:28:50.480
and it's a really good example of a lot of
retouching and airbrushing on a photograph.

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:55.090
So put that back carefully.

00:28:55.090 --> 00:28:58.820
We also have a preparator in our department
