image, but she's really poking at the question

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:27.440
of, like, what's an original and what's a
copy,

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:31.789
have originals historically favored reputations
of male artists,

00:32:31.789 --> 00:32:36.140
where the idea of multiplicity of lack of
originality

00:32:36.140 --> 00:32:41.120
might be something new that she and artists
of her generation in the '80s were exploring.

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:47.399
And so she's not trying to imitate the tonality,
and she often includes little cues that help

00:32:47.399 --> 00:32:52.159
you understand that what she's making isn't
the same as the original.

00:32:52.159 --> 00:32:53.929
It's her version of it.

00:32:53.929 --> 00:32:59.929
So it is a really complex question.

00:32:59.929 --> 00:33:07.919
There was an artist, not that long ago who
actually made copies of Sherrie Levine's photographs.

00:33:07.919 --> 00:33:11.110
I think, if you google it, you'll find it.

00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:15.710
Adding another layer to this idea of what's
considered appropriation.

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:22.409
And it is perfectly permissible to appropriate
work in pursuit of making another work of

00:33:22.409 --> 00:33:23.409
art.

00:33:23.409 --> 00:33:32.120
And so this fall pretty squarely into that
category, which is why they're okay.

