00:36:32.779 --> 00:36:39.150
So this one has not only Mylar, that's that,
but it also has a sheet of what we call photo

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:45.469
text, because these are super fragile and
a photogram means that it's unique.

00:36:45.469 --> 00:36:50.519
So take down the Mylar, remove the photo text.

00:36:50.519 --> 00:36:52.660
I'll leave this open like this.

00:36:52.660 --> 00:36:57.759
So yes, when Man...and I'm gonna actually
talk behind it, because God forbid, I should

00:36:57.759 --> 00:36:59.589
spit on that photograph.

00:36:59.589 --> 00:37:02.229
So, Man Ray, when he made these photograms.

00:37:02.229 --> 00:37:08.859
This is a unique contact print, which means
that he took little glass stoppers from maybe

00:37:08.859 --> 00:37:12.859
crystal bottles and a little bit of gauze

00:37:12.859 --> 00:37:19.420
and a little piece of wire that he put in
a cube and two other things that I can't quite

00:37:19.420 --> 00:37:20.680
figure out what they are,

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:26.319
but he placed all of those things directly
onto a piece of photographic paper and then

00:37:26.319 --> 00:37:29.469
he turned on the light, and then turned off
the light.

00:37:29.469 --> 00:37:35.349
And in that exposure, anywhere where the light
could get through to the paper, it became

00:37:35.349 --> 00:37:36.349
dark.

00:37:36.349 --> 00:37:38.959
And anywhere the light was blocked, it remained
white.

00:37:38.959 --> 00:37:41.130
So this is something that's opaque.

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:44.190
This is sort of semitransparent, like the
glass.

00:37:44.190 --> 00:37:47.279
And then the black was where the light shone
straight through.

00:37:47.279 --> 00:37:53.760
So, yes, the photograms actually are unique,
and they are not made with a camera, which

00:37:53.760 --> 00:37:56.970
is partly why they're so precious and we wanna
take care of them.

00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:01.910
And thanks to James Thrall Soby, when these
group of pictures came to the collection in

00:38:01.910 --> 00:38:03.020
